    <section id="id1169321433000">
      <title>Phosphorous trihalides</title>
      <para id="id1169320302662">Phosphorous trihalides, PX<sub>3</sub>, are produced from the direct reaction of phosphorous with the appropriate halogen, <link target-id="eip-127"/>. The fluoride is readily made from the halide exchange reaction of PCl<sub>3</sub> with fluoride salts, <link target-id="eip-566"/>. Mixed trihalides are formed by halide exchange, <link target-id="eip-988"/>. </para>
      
      <equation id="eip-127"><media id="id1169314928812_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics1-c015.jpg" id="id1169314928812__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
        </media>
      </equation>
      <equation id="eip-566"><media id="id1169314882849_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics2-a831.jpg" id="id1169314882849__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
        </media>
      </equation>
      <equation id="eip-988"><media id="id1169324118710_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics3-4902.jpg" id="id1169324118710__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
        </media>
      </equation><para id="id2981062">A summary of the physical properties of the phosphorous trihalides is given in <link target-id="id1169321512062"/>. All the compounds have a pyramidal structure in the vapor phase and in solution. </para>
